material.mattext: Cohesion is the ability of a module to be independent from other modules.
True
False
Modules are not necessary to use when programming.
True
False
Modules should have a designated function.
True
False
The value of a local variable is available to all other modules.
True
False
The value of a parameter is available to all other modules.
True
False
The value of a global variable is available to all other modules.
True
False
A solution is just as easy to read and understand if it is written in one module or many modules.
True
False
The use of modules many times eliminates rewriting the same instructions.
True
False
The Wrap-up module processes only those instructions that are at the end of a series of other modules before continuing to other modules.
True
False
The actual parameter listing is the list of parameters that follow the module name at the beginning of the module.
True
False
Coupling allows:
Data to be passed from one module to all other modules.
Data to be passes from one module to another module.
Data to be unavailable to other modules.
Instructions to be available to other modules.
Data can be made available to other modules through the use of:
Parameters.
Global variables.
Return values.
All of the above.
Call-by-reference parameters pass values:
By passing the value of the variable.
By making the variable global.
By passing the memory location of the variable.
None of the above.
A coupling diagram shows:
How the data is passed from one module to another.
The test values of the variables.
How the modules process the data.
Where the variables are located in the modules.
The data dictionary is:
A list of definitions of words used in the development of the solution.
A list of definitions and attributes of the variables used in the solution.
A table the computer uses internally to define the memory location of the variables.
A table of values to test the solution of the problem.
Cohesion relates to:
The ability to share data between modules.
The ability to have local variables shared between modules.
The functional independence of each module.
All of the above.
Modules should:
Have one function.
Have one entrance and one exit.
Be short and easily read.
All of the above.
a and c.
Calculations may be found:
In any module.
Only in the calculation modules.
Only in any process modules.
Any module but the Wrap-up module.
Call-by-value parameters:
Pass the changed value back to the calling module.
Can be changed in the called module.
Pass the unchanged (original) value back to the calling module.
Cannot be changed in the called module.
b and c.
c and d.
The variable names in the formal and actual parameter listings:
Must be the same.
May be the same.
Cannot be the same.
Only the call-by-value names must be the same.
The sequential logic structure:
Processes instructions in order of listing.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two paths to follow.
Allows the computer to repeat instructions.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two or more paths to follow.
The decision logic structure:
Processes instructions in order of listing.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two paths to follow.
Allows the computer to repeat instructions.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two or more paths to follow.
The loop logic structure:
Processes instructions in order of listing.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two paths to follow.
Allows the computer to repeat instructions.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two or more paths to follow.
The case logic structure within the decision logic structure:
Processes instructions in order of listing.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two paths to follow.
Allows the computer to repeat instructions.
Allows the computer to make a choice of two or more paths to follow.
The values of local variables:
Are defined within a module.
Are defined within the calling module.
Can only be changed within the module.
Are available to any called module.
